        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity and requested wavelength band:  
We have carefully considered the optimal wavelength band to achieve our goals using CASA simulations.  Given the spectral slope of the continuum emission of interest, Band 7 observations are most efficient.  We request 0.025 mJy rms sensitivity, driven by the desire to obtain a solid (5 x rms) detection of the stellar photosphere, which is known to be 0.15 mJy at 870 microns.  (A detection of the stellar photosphere with the same signal-to-noise in Band 6 would require almost twice as much time on-source, according to the Sensitivity Calculator.)  Our simulations (Figures 2 and 3) show that this sensitivity will provide a typical signal-to-noise of &gt; 15 per beam on the HD 10647 dust belt emission, sufficient to achieve our goal of constraining its location and detailed shape. The spectral line aspect is a secondary detection experiment only; the observations will be sensitive to CO(3-2) line emission of 11 mJy (5 x rms) per beam per 0.85 km/s velocity bin.

Imaging requirements:  
We require angular resolution high enough to (1) resolve the structure of the emission belt, (2) cleanly separate the stellar photosphere from the belt, and (3) solidly detect centroid offsets corresponding to eccentricities of e &lt; 0.1 (Figure 2, third panel).  All of these requirements drive the needed beam size to &lt; 1 arcsec.  The maximum angular scale of interest is the full extent of the emission belt.  While this full extent is nominally about 10 arcsec, the relevant largest scale is effectively the few arcsec width of the highly inclined emission belt.  Our simulations of model belts show that the total flux is readily recovered by the shortest beaselines of the main array (Figure 3); thus, the ACA is not required.  The full extent of the source emission fits well within a single pointing at Band 7.  Dynamic range is not a problem.

Correlator setup:  
This is primarily a continuum project, so we configure the correlator in order to achieve the maximum 7.5 GHz bandwidth for maximum continuum sensitivity.  We place one spectral window on the CO J=3-2 line with resolution 0.976 MHz (0.85 km/s), sufficient to resolve orbital velocities at 10's of AU around this Sun-like star.

Calibration:  
No additional calibrations are required for this project.

Bandpass accuracy:  
Standard calibration is sufficient.

Scheduling/time constraints:  
This project is not time constrained and can be scheduled dynamically.

Data rate: 
Within normal limtits.

Special constraints on standard observing modes:  
None

</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
