    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Millimeter imaging of debris disks provides unique information because the large grains that dominate at these long wavelengths have dynamics similar to otherwise invisible dust-producing planetismals.  We propose to spatially resolve the millimeter emission from the HD 10647 system, a nearby (17.4 pc) Sun-like star (F9V) with a Jupiter-like radial velocity planet and the most luminous debris disk in the Solar neighborhood.  The proximity and exceptionally strong excess emission make this system a cornerstone template for the interpretation of debris disks around Solar analogs.  The disk shows signs of asymmetries in far-infrared emission and scattered light that point to the presence of an additional planet on a wide separation orbit.  With ALMA, we will characterize the location and distribution of planetesimals orbiting HD 10647 in unprecedented detail, constraining the radial emission gradient, boundaries, and azimuthal asymmetries.  The simultaneous detection of the stellar photosphere results in very accurate relative astrometry to quantify any stellocentric offset of the disk corresponding to an eccentricity induced by a wide separation planet. </prp:abstract>
